In a press briefing, Secretary of State Mike Pompeo provided an update on the upcoming summit between President Trump and Chairman Kim Jong Un. He addressed a report in The New York Times that questioned the technical expertise of the U.S. team in dismantling North Korea's weapons program, stating that an interagency working group of over 100 experts has been meeting for over three months to address technical and logistical issues. He also emphasized that the U.S. will only accept the complete, verifiable, and irreversible denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula and that sanctions will remain until North Korea eliminates its weapons of mass destruction programs. Pompeo expressed optimism about the summit and the potential for a successful outcome. He also stated that President Trump is fully prepared for the meeting and that the U.S. is prepared to provide security assurances to North Korea. Pompeo did not provide specific details on the discussions or the possibility of removing U.S. forces from South Korea. When asked about trust between the U.S. and North Korea, Pompeo emphasized the need for verification and stated that both countries will have to come to have sufficient trust in each other. He also addressed the recent tensions between the U.S. and its European allies, stating that the relationships will continue to move forward on a strong basis.